{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS-1 REVIEW (G6 ‚Äî approach soundness) of story B4 (Planned-trace parity harness). One mechanism-completeness finding; rationale + approach-selection affirmed.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (G6 criteria passed):\n- FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE / positive rationale (G6.2, G6.4): The \"Why\" states a strong, correct positive rationale ‚Äî assert PLANNED-trace parity, NOT result parity, because \"the review is LLM-dependent and variable.\" This is the right proxy-avoidance: it validates that both implementations ISSUE the same plan rather than trusting equivalent LLM output. PASS.\n- APPROACH SELECTION (G6.3): The central design choice (planned-trace parity vs. the obvious alternative, result/output parity) is defensible and well-argued; the offline FakeRunner corpus over a diverse scenario set (container/leaf, overlays, code-grounded, oversize, missing-AC) is at-least-as-good on testability + blast-radius (no live calls/credentials, CI-able) than a live golden-output approach. The pre-escalation-only assertion correctly tolerates non-deterministic size-ladder escalation. No clearly-superior alternative missed. PASS.\n\nFINDING (G6.1 mechanism correctness ‚Äî incomplete trace-capture seam):\nThe \"What\"/\"Scope\" describe the harness as running \"via the Fake runner\" (singular) and lean on Epic A's `PlannedTraceRunner` (an `AgentStepRunner`, src/rebar/llm/workflow/trace.py:22). But per this epic's own design note (docs/design/batch-runner-seam.md:149-157, 169-173 ‚Äî the critique's MAJOR 4), the planned trace MUST be assembled from TWO offline-fakeable capture points: (a) the batch's `rebar.llm.Runner` for the FINDER calls and (b) the engine's `AgentStepRunner` for the Pass-2 verify step. The finder is `passes.pass1_chunk(runner: Runner, ...)` (src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py:186-212) ‚Äî it drives a `rebar.llm.Runner` DIRECTLY, NOT an `AgentStepRunner`; D3 (batch-runner-seam.md:74-81) confirms the production runner owns its own injectable `rebar.llm.Runner` and the seam's `agent_runner` is intentionally unused. Consequence (batch-runner-seam.md:155-157): \"the batch's internal finder calls are NOT visible to the engine's generic `PlannedTraceRunner`/dry-run ‚Äî they're traced one level down.\" As written, B4's mechanism could be implemented to capture only the `AgentStepRunner` seam, which would assert parity on a trace MISSING the finder calls ‚Äî i.e. the prompt-id + intended-model + call-mode events that ARE the parity payload (epic AC3). The plan should make the dual-seam capture explicit so the implementer wires BOTH a fake `rebar.llm.Runner` (finder/criteria events) AND the `PlannedTraceRunner`/`AgentStepRunner` (verify event) and concatenates them into the ordered planned trace it diffs.\n\n- [ ] Make explicit that the planned-trace harness captures at BOTH seams ‚Äî a fake/tracing `rebar.llm.Runner` injected into the production batch runner (for the finder/criteria calls, which are NOT visible to the engine's `AgentStepRunner`-level `PlannedTraceRunner`) AND the engine `AgentStepRunner` seam (for the Pass-2 verify step) ‚Äî and that the asserted trace is the ordered concatenation of both; otherwise the harness diffs an incomplete trace missing the finder events that are the parity payload.\nlocation: B4 \"What\"/\"Scope\" sections; src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py:186; docs/design/batch-runner-seam.md:155-173\ncriteria: G6"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782448076363148001,"uuid":"13e3d08d-c58b-4156-a0d1-f32ce1699309"}